2. Communication: Clear and concise communication with your teammates can mean the difference between winning and losing a round.
3. Learning map layouts: Familiarizing yourself with the map layout enables you to position yourself strategically, anticipate enemy movement and set your aim faster.
4. Equipment: Make sure to spend your money wisely in buying equipment. Timing smokes, flashbangs, and knowing when to go for a full buy could turn the tide of the game.
5. Competition: Regularly play against opponents who are better than you. This can highlight areas for improvement and make you adapt to different playstyles.
Remember, patience and practice are key. You're not going to become amazing overnight, but as long as you're constantly learning and improving, you're on the right track.
